node.text: The 1stDibs NFT marketplace is officially open, and you’re invited to bid on high-caliber crypto art by the most innovative creators in the space. On the occasion of our first exhibition Portals: Art on the Threshold, we visited 1stDibs curator and artist @Metageist_, along with fellow artists @Process_Smith and @ogianima, in London, England. The leading artists, who also consider themselves NFT buyers and collectors, take us through the process of creating non-fungible tokens through VR and discuss the future of digital art. Explore NFT auctions on 1stDibs at the link in bio.

node.text: In our latest edition of “On Location,” we’re thrilled to showcase the new home collection (@sirianointeriors) by award-winning fashion designer and CFDA member Christian Siriano (@csiriano), which is debuting exclusively on 1stDibs. He takes us into his “dusty but fabulous” studio for a behind-the-scenes peek at his beautifully crafted work. As with his statement-making clothes, Christian’s furniture designs all start with a sketch and are inspired by everything from candy (see the gumdrop stool) to old movies and picnics in the park. Click the link in bio to shop the chic, sartorially-inspired collection.

node.text: Join us for a new edition of “On Location,” in which we visit fine art embroiderer @richardsaja in his Catskill, NY, studio. Richard’s work is a kind of meditation in which time evaporates in a blur of color and stitching. He transforms classical mediums—toile fabrics and tapestries—with what he refers to as “historical inaccuracy.” Surrounded by a rainbow palette of embroidery floss, he takes a coloring book approach to pastoral scenes. They emerge infused with contemporary issues and cultural memes that celebrate difference and encourage tolerance. Click the link in bio to discover more of Richard’s enchanting embroidered, decorative, graphic and fine art pieces.

node.title: On Location With Fine Art Embroiderer Richard Saja

node.text: Is an engagement ring from the Victorian era (1837-1901) calling your name? These feminine designs often feature small rose cut or old mine cut diamonds, along with ornate patterns hammered into the gold settings. Romantic motifs include hearts, flowers and stars, but the swirling two-stone toi et moi rings are perhaps the ultimate symbol of an eternal bond. Click the link in bio to watch the full video on shopping for vintage or antique rings.

node.title: Victorian, Edwardian and Art Deco Rings on 1stDibs

node.text: Our latest edition of “On Location: Personal Space” takes us into the light-drenched Brooklyn duplex of Milan-born designer Mario Milana and his wife, the Colombian actress Gabriella Campagna. His simple and efficient morning routine sets him up for a quarantine day of painting, reading, soaking up sunshine in the back garden and more meditation—seated in his low-slung Asana chair, of course!

node.text: Next up in our new series, “On Location: Personal Space,” we spend a little time with potter, designer and author @jonathanadler. Where better to shelter in place alongside his husband—writer and fashion icon (and videographer!) @simondoonan— and their dog Foxy than the gorgeous home they share on Shelter Island? With its bright palette, groovy furnishings and sweeping ocean views, it’s the ideal place to work and play. Surrounded by his own creations and collections, Jonathan is managing to drink tea, practice his pull-ups and do a lot of reading.

The homeowners came to @jwsinteriors for a modern, natural vibe with a touch of glamour. node.text: Brazilian designer @sergiojmatos draws heavily on the rich artisanal culture of Brazil’s Northeast to create what he calls a “cultural cauldron with mestizo seasoning.” The result is compelling pieces like this Biboca Swing chair, inspired by the simple houses of the indigenous Tupi Guarani people. Nautical ropes in a geometric weave on an aluminum base create an invitation to levitate in a place of lightness and warmth. Click the link in bio to explore more. 📸: @sergiojmatos

node.text: The partners behind interior design firm @cardencunietti, Audrey Carden and Eleanora Cunietti, work out of a shared office in London but mostly manage their projects—luxurious homes, yachts, private planes, a clubhouse on a private soccer field and even a personal nightclub—separately. It fell to Carden to re-enliven this 19th-century Westminster villa from which all the charming period details had previously been expunged. She decided not to undertake a faithful restoration but rather to add dazzling elements that would transform it into a jewel box. Large glass panels by the Cypriot artist Yorgos Papadopoulos flank a doorway to the dining room, where a work by Dale Frank hangs. Click the link in bio to see more in Introspective. 📸: @gg_archard

The influential French ceramicist, Roger Capron, is known for his use of recurring motifs such as stylized branches and geometrical suns. After studying at the Applied Arts School in Paris, he co-founded a ceramics workshop, l’Atelier Callis, that contributed to the renaissance of French ceramics. The work produced there garnered many awards, including the Grand Prix International de la Céramique in 1970. This ceramic Bird Pitcher Vase is signed by the artist. Photo: 📸: Galerie Sandy Toupenet

node.text: The Italian designer Gigi Sabadin is known for inventive designs in bent plywood. These streamlined chairs from the 1970s, produced by Stilwood, have a veneered finish. The floating shape is created with three legs and an open backrest that adds a sense of lightness. On top of their good looks, the chairs are stackable and easy to store. Click the link in bio to shop. 📸: @morentz_gallery

node.text: Sigma L2’s table lamp is formed out of one sinuously curved iron tube from which many smaller iron tubes extend horizontally. All the iron elements are soldered together by hand and can be plated in gold or chrome. The interior of the brown silk shade can also be adorned in paler gold or silver to create striking reflections. This customization is made possible by the expert craftsmanship of the artisans of Sigma L2, a factory founded 30 years ago by Paolo Granchi. 📸: The Craftcode

node.text: The 1stDibs NFT marketplace is officially open, and you’re invited to bid on high-caliber crypto art by the most innovative creators in the space. On the occasion of our first exhibition Portals: Art on the Threshold, we visited 1stDibs curator and artist @Metageist_, along with fellow artists @Process_Smith and @ogianima, in London, England. The leading artists, who also consider themselves NFT buyers and collectors, take us through the process of creating non-fungible tokens through VR and discuss the future of digital art. node.text: Designed in 1970 by the legendary Italian architect, industrial designer, philosopher and provocateur, Ettore Sottsass, the Ultrafragola mirror foreshadows the work created by the Memphis Group, which mocked high status design by building furniture with inexpensive materials. Ultrafragola, with its conspicuously curved molded fiberglass shell and radical pops of pink neon, is both functional and a bit shocking, in the best possible way. Click the link in bio to shop. 📸: @spaceandchrome

node.text: “I think of myself as a visual storyteller through design,” says #1stDibs50 designer Sheila Bridges (@harlemtoilegirl). “Everyone has a story to tell.” Her own unfolds across the double-height dining room of her Hudson Valley home, a repository for the art and objects she’s made or assembled over a — yes, storied — career. There are vintage Fornasetti chairs. There are Louis XV fauteuils, re-covered in pony skin. There are Moroccan carpets, gathered on endless trips to a country she loves for its wild embrace of color, which she shares. And there is a custom mobile by Elizabeth Parker (@blanche.jelly), kinetic eye candy in a space not lacking for drama. Still, Bridges puts contemporary photographs (by Lorna Simpson and Fabiola Jean-Louis) at the room’s center. These are her stories within stories. Click the link in bio to discover the rest of the home, and to meet all of this year’s 1stDibs 50 honorees. 📸: @frankfrancesstudio
